## 4. Documentation ‚ÄĒ Sphinx + sphinx-needs

All design documentation lives in `docs/` and is built with **Sphinx**. We use
**sphinx-needs** for full traceability between requirements, architecture decisions,
implementation, and tests.

### Need types and ID prefixes

| Type | Prefix | Purpose |
|------|--------|---------|
| Requirement | `REQ-` | What the system must do |
| User story / usability | `UC-` | User-facing acceptance criteria |
| Architecture decision | `ADR-` | Recorded design choices (one `.rst` per ADR) |
| Specification | `SPEC-` | Detailed designs |
| Implementation | `IMPL-` | Pointer to code (file + symbol) |
| Test | `TEST-` | A pytest test case |

### Traceability rules

- Every `REQ-` links to ‚Č• 1 `SPEC-` and ‚Č• 1 `TEST-` via `links:`.
- Every `ADR-` references the `REQ-`/`SPEC-` it serves and the `IMPL-` it produced.
- Every `IMPL-` names the source file and symbol; code docstrings echo the ID in a
  `Needs:` footer (see ¬ß2 example).
- Every `TEST-` references the `pytest` node id (e.g. `tests/test_trips.py::test_add`).
- The Sphinx build runs with `-W` (warnings as errors) and **fails** if any need has
  a dangling/missing link.

### Required Sphinx extensions

`sphinx`, `sphinx-needs`, `sphinxcontrib-mermaid`, `sphinx-autodoc`, `sphinx-copybutton`,
`myst-parser` (so we can author in Markdown where preferred).

### Coverage of generated reports inside docs

The Sphinx build embeds:

- `coverage` HTML report (linked from `docs/reports/coverage.rst`)
- `mutmut` HTML report (linked from `docs/reports/mutation.rst`)
- pytest results / JUnit summary (linked from `docs/reports/tests.rst`)
- `pip-audit` and `bandit` summaries (`docs/reports/security.rst`)

---

## 5. Architecture Diagrams ‚ÄĒ Mermaid

- All architecture/sequence/ERD diagrams are authored as **Mermaid** in
  `docs/diagrams/*.md` and embedded in Sphinx via `sphinxcontrib-mermaid`.
- Maintain at minimum:
  - **C4 context** diagram of the system
  - **Container/component** diagram of the Flask app
  - **ERD** of the SQLite schema
  - **Sequence diagram** for each user-facing flow (plan a weekend, save a trip, ‚Ä¶)
- A code change that alters architecture **must** update the relevant diagram in the
  same change set.

Example block:

````markdown
```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
  actor User
  User->>Flask: POST /trips
  Flask->>Service: create_trip(payload)
  Service->>SQLite: INSERT INTO trips ...
  SQLite-->>Service: row id
  Service-->>Flask: Trip
  Flask-->>User: 201 Created
```
````

