## 6. Requirements Management

- Authoritative requirements live in `docs/requirements/*.rst` as `req` directives.
- Each `REQ-` has: title, description, status (`draft|approved|implemented|verified`),
  priority (`low|medium|high|critical`), source/owner.
- Reference at least one `REQ-` in every commit message and PR description.
- Changes to a `REQ-` require an `ADR-` if they break or substantially alter scope.

---

## 7. Testing ‚ÄĒ pytest, coverage, mutation

### Framework and layout

- **pytest** as the runner. Tests under `tests/`, mirroring `app/`.
- File names `test_<module>.py`; test names `test_<unit>__<scenario>__<expected>`.
- AAA pattern (Arrange / Act / Assert), one logical assertion per test.
- Shared fixtures in `tests/conftest.py` (Flask test client, temp DB, factory data).
- Use **hypothesis** for property-based tests where input space matters.

### Coverage

- `pytest-cov` with **line and branch** coverage.
- Threshold: **‚Č• 80%** overall, enforced via `--cov-fail-under=80`.
- New/changed code must have **‚Č• 90%** coverage on its module.
- Exclusions live in `pyproject.toml` `[tool.coverage.*]` and must be justified by a
  comment.

### Mutation testing

- **mutmut** runs against `app/` (and `database.py` until refactored).
- **Mutation score ‚Č• 70%** overall; surviving mutants are either killed by new tests
  or recorded with rationale in `docs/reports/mutation.rst`.
- Run mutation testing at minimum on every PR that touches business logic.

### Test types

| Layer | Tool | Notes |
|-------|------|-------|
| Unit | pytest | Pure functions, services, models |
| Integration | pytest + Flask test client | Routes, blueprints, DB |
| Property | hypothesis | Parsers, validators, date math |
| Smoke | pytest | One end-to-end happy-path test per flow |
| Usability | manual + Lighthouse + axe | See ¬ß8 |

---

## 8. Usability Testing

- Each user-facing feature has a `UC-###` need with acceptance criteria.
- Manual usability checklist lives at `docs/usability/checklist.md`. Run it for any UI
  change. It covers: task completion, error recovery, mobile responsiveness,
  keyboard navigation, screen-reader labels.
- Templates must meet **WCAG 2.1 AA**. Verify with `axe-core` (browser extension or
  `pytest-axe`) and document results in `docs/reports/accessibility.rst`.
- **Lighthouse** scores ‚Č• 90 for Performance, Accessibility, Best Practices, SEO on
  every page in production mode.
- Forms have visible labels, helpful error messages, and CSRF tokens.

---

## 9. Security

- **Never** commit secrets. Configuration via env vars and `.env` (loaded with
  `python-dotenv`); commit `.env.example` only.
- All SQL goes through **parameterised queries** ‚ÄĒ never string concatenation/f-strings.
- All forms use **Flask-WTF** with CSRF protection.
- Validate and sanitise all user input at the boundary (WTForms validators / pydantic).
- Set safe response headers (CSP, X-Frame-Options, Referrer-Policy) ‚ÄĒ use
  `flask-talisman` or equivalent.
- Run `pip-audit` and `bandit -r app/` in CI; both must pass.

---

## 10. Logging & Error Handling

- Configure the standard `logging` module via `app.logger` / `logging.config.dictConfig`.
- Structured log lines with timestamp, level, request id, and user (if any).
- Define custom exception classes in `app/errors.py`; catch specific exceptions only.
- Map exceptions to HTTP responses via Flask error handlers; never leak stack traces
  to users.

---

## 11. Configuration & Dependencies

- Runtime deps in `requirements.txt`; dev/test/docs deps in `requirements-dev.txt`.
- Pin **all** versions (`==`); refresh deliberately, not incidentally.
- Tool config (Black, Ruff, isort, mypy, pytest, coverage, mutmut) lives in
  `pyproject.toml`.
- Use `python-dotenv`; `Config` classes for `Development`, `Testing`, `Production`.

---

## 12. Git, Commits, and PR Workflow

- **Conventional Commits**: `feat:`, `fix:`, `docs:`, `test:`, `refactor:`, `chore:`,
  `perf:`, `style:`, `build:`, `ci:`. Reference `REQ-`/`ADR-` IDs in the body.
- One concern per PR. Every PR updates code **and** tests **and** docs together.
- Pre-commit hooks enforce Black, isort, Ruff, mypy, and a Sphinx warning-free build
  on changed `.rst`/`.md`.

---

## 13. Definition of Done

A task is **not** complete until **every** box is checked:

- [ ] Code passes Black, isort, Ruff, mypy with no warnings
- [ ] File/function/complexity limits respected (¬ß3)
- [ ] Public APIs have Google-style docstrings with `Needs:` footers
- [ ] Unit + integration tests added/updated; overall coverage ‚Č• 80%, changed
      modules ‚Č• 90%
- [ ] Mutation score ‚Č• 70% on changed modules (mutmut)
- [ ] Sphinx docs updated; `sphinx-build -W` passes; sphinx-needs links resolve
- [ ] Mermaid diagrams updated where architecture changed
- [ ] `REQ-`/`ADR-` IDs referenced in commit and PR description
- [ ] For UI changes: manual usability checklist + Lighthouse + axe results recorded
- [ ] `pip-audit` and `bandit` clean
- [ ] No secrets committed; `.env.example` reflects any new variables

---

## 14. Agent Workflow ‚ÄĒ How To Apply These Rules

When taking on a task, the agent should:

1. **Read the request and the relevant `REQ-`/`ADR-`** before editing.
2. Plan the change in small steps; if it touches > 5 files or changes architecture,
   surface a brief plan and proposed `ADR-` first.
3. Make the smallest correct edit. Stay under the size limits in ¬ß3.
4. Add or update tests in the same change. Run them locally where possible.
5. Update `docs/` (requirements, ADRs, diagrams, reports) in the same change.
6. Run through the ¬ß13 Definition of Done before declaring success.
7. If a rule must be bent for a good reason, **say so explicitly** and link an
   `ADR-` that records the exception.
